description: From Middle English alien, a borrowing from Old French alien, aliene, from Latin aliēnus (“belonging to someone else, later exotic, foreign”), from Latin alius (“other”), from Proto-Indo-European *h₂élyos. Related to English else.

adjectives.description: alien (comparative more alien, superlative most alien)

entries.meaning: Not belonging to the same country, land, or government, or to the citizens or subjects thereof; foreign.
examples: alien subjects, enemies, property, or shores

entries.meaning: Pertaining to extraterrestrial life; typical of an extraterrestrial creature.
Any life form of extraterrestrial or extradimensional origin.
A person, animal, plant, or other thing which is from outside the family, group, organization, or territory under consideration.
A foreigner residing in a country.
One excluded from certain privileges; one alienated or estranged.

verbs.description: alien (third-person singular simple present aliens, present participle aliening, simple past and past participle aliened)

entries.meaning: (law) To transfer the ownership of something.
